name: Titanium.Media.MusicPlayer
doc:
@platform iphone 1.4.0 @platform ipad 1.4.0 @editurl https://github.com/appcelerator/titanium_mobile/edit/master/apidoc/Titanium/Media/MusicPlayer.yml

This object represents a music controller.

@description

A MusicPlayer lets you manage and playback a queue of media Item objects.

To retrieve an instance of a MusicPlayer object, use either the Titanium.Media.appMusicPlayer or the Titanium.Media.systemMusicPlayer property.

Use the Media module's openMusicLibrary and queryMusicLibrary methods to access the media items in the device's media library.

property.name: apiName
property.doc:
The name of the API that this proxy corresponds to.

@description

The value of this property is the fully qualified name of the API. For example, Button returns Ti.UI.Button.

@platform android 3.2.0 @platform blackberry 3.2.0 @platform iphone 3.2.0 @platform ipad 3.2.0 @platform mobileweb 3.2.0
property.shortDoc: The name of the API that this proxy corresponds to. ...

property.name: bubbleParent
property.doc:
Indicates if the proxy will bubble an event to its parent.

@description

Some proxies (most commonly views) have a relationship to other proxies, often established by the add() method. For example, for a button added to a window, a click event on the button would bubble up to the window. Other common parents are table sections to their rows, table views to their sections, and scrollable views to their views. Set this property to false to disable the bubbling to the proxy's parent.

@platform android 3.0.0 @platform iphone 3.0.0 @platform ipad 3.0.0
property.shortDoc: Indicates if the proxy will bubble an event to its parent. ...

property.name: currentPlaybackTime
property.doc:
Current point in song playback, in seconds.

@description

This property is read/write, so you can update the music player's current position by setting this property.
property.shortDoc: Current point in song playback, in seconds. ...

property.name: lifecycleContainer
property.doc:
The Window or TabGroup whose Activity lifecycle should be triggered on the proxy.

@description

If this property is set to a Window or TabGroup, then the corresponding Activity lifecycle event callbacks will also be called on the proxy. Proxies that require the activity lifecycle will need this property set to the appropriate containing Window or TabGroup.

@platform android 3.6.0
property.shortDoc: The Window or TabGroup whose Activity lifecycle should be triggered on the proxy. ...

property.name: nowPlaying
property.doc: An Item object representing the currently playing media item.

property.name: playbackState
property.doc:
Playback state.

This API can be assigned the following constants:

  • Titanium.Media.MUSIC_PLAYER_STATE_INTERRUPTED
  • Titanium.Media.MUSIC_PLAYER_STATE_PAUSED
  • Titanium.Media.MUSIC_PLAYER_STATE_PLAYING
  • Titanium.Media.MUSIC_PLAYER_STATE_SEEK_BACKWARD
  • Titanium.Media.MUSIC_PLAYER_STATE_SEEK_FORWARD
  • Titanium.Media.MUSIC_PLAYER_STATE_STOPPED

property.name: repeatMode
property.doc:
Repeat setting.

This API can be assigned the following constants:

  • Titanium.Media.MUSIC_PLAYER_REPEAT_ALL
  • Titanium.Media.MUSIC_PLAYER_REPEAT_DEFAULT
  • Titanium.Media.MUSIC_PLAYER_REPEAT_NONE
  • Titanium.Media.MUSIC_PLAYER_REPEAT_ONE

property.name: shuffleMode
property.doc:
Shuffle setting.

This API can be assigned the following constants:

  • Titanium.Media.MUSIC_PLAYER_SHUFFLE_ALBUMS
  • Titanium.Media.MUSIC_PLAYER_SHUFFLE_DEFAULT
  • Titanium.Media.MUSIC_PLAYER_SHUFFLE_NONE
  • Titanium.Media.MUSIC_PLAYER_SHUFFLE_SONGS

property.name: volume
property.doc:
Volume level for the music player from 0.0 (muted) to 1.0 (loudest).

Requires: iOS 7.0 and earlier

@description

This property has no effect on devices running iOS 8.0 and later.

This adjusts the volume of the application's session.

The iOS simulator ignores this volume setting. This is a known issue with Apple's simulator.
property.shortDoc: Volume level for the music player from 0.0 (muted) to 1.0 (loudest). ...

method.name: removeEventListener
method.doc:
Removes the specified callback as an event listener for the named event.

@description

Multiple listeners can be registered for the same event, so the callback parameter is used to determine which listener to remove.

When adding a listener, you must save a reference to the callback function in order to remove the listener later:

var listener = function() { Ti.API.info("Event listener called."); }
window.addEventListener('click', listener);

To remove the listener, pass in a reference to the callback function:

window.removeEventListener('click', listener);

params.name: name
params.doc: Name of the event.

params.name: callback
params.doc: Callback function to remove. Must be the same function passed to addEventListener.

method.shortDoc: Removes the specified callback as an event listener for the named event. ...

method.name: seekBackward
method.doc:
Begins seeking backward in the currently playing media.

@description

Seeking speed increases as seeking continues.

Call stopSeeking to return to normal play.
method.shortDoc: Begins seeking backward in the currently playing media. ...

method.name: seekForward
method.doc:
Begins seeking forward in the currently playing media item.

@description

While seeking forward audio plays faster than usual. The speed increases as seeking continues.

Call stopSeeking to return to normal play.
method.shortDoc: Begins seeking forward in the currently playing media item. ...
